english:
  title: Passing Through the Qing Captive Fort
  author: Kim Hui-je
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The general grasps his axe, yet shame remains unwashed—
    With what face shall he present himself at Heaven's gate?
    One stroke of the green serpent pointed toward Ma Mountain,
    And the barbarian hordes seemed ready to collapse.
    Tiger-warriors soared and leaped across five rivers,
    Walls and bastions all reduced to ash and embers.
    Raising the cup, a man's heart finds release—
    But turning back with no face to show, sweat falls in shame.
  footnotes:
    - 'Ma Mountain (마산): A reference to a battlefield or strategic location symbolizing military engagement.'
    - 'Green serpent (푸른 뱀): A poetic metaphor for the general''s sword or blade.'
    - 'Tiger-warriors (호분): Elite soldiers or cavalry known for their courage and prowess.'
    - 'Five rivers: Likely a reference to major river crossings during military campaigns, symbolizing the vastness of conquered territory.'
